# Git Workflow Rules — Autopsy

## The Golden Rule
**One story = one commit. Always. No exceptions.**

## Autonomous Execution Mode
Cursor works through ALL stories in STORIES.md automatically without stopping.
- Complete a story → commit → immediately start the next story
- Do NOT ask "should I continue?", "ready for the next one?", or "shall I proceed?"
- Do NOT wait for human approval between stories
- Do NOT summarize what you just did and pause — just keep going
- The only valid reason to stop is a failure you cannot resolve after 3 attempts
- If blocked after 3 attempts: write `BLOCKED.md` explaining what failed, commit it as `chore(SX.Y): note blocker`, then move on to the next story
- Run through every story from S0.1 to S7.4 in one uninterrupted session

## Story Execution — Exact Sequence Per Story

```bash
# 1. Read the story from STORIES.md completely before writing any code

# 2. Implement everything the story requires

# 3. Run checks — ALL must pass before committing
go test -race ./...
go vet ./...
go build ./...

# 4. Stage and commit
git add -A
git commit -m "feat(SX.Y): short description matching the story"

# 5. Verify the commit landed
git log --oneline -1

# 6. Immediately begin the next story — no pause
```

## Commit Message Format
```
<type>(<story-id>): <short description>

Types:
  feat     — new feature or functionality
  fix      — bug fix
  chore    — tooling, dependencies, config
  docs     — documentation only
  test     — test files only
  refactor — code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
```

Examples:
```
chore(S0.1): initialize go module and air live-reload
chore(S0.2): env config, API key guard, stub mode flag
feat(S1.2): streaming tar.gz extraction to temp dir
feat(S3.3): phase 3 streaming RCA with kubectl remediation steps
fix(S2.3): handle missing log directory gracefully
feat(S7.2): multi-stage Dockerfile with non-root user
docs(S7.4): final README polish and v1.0.0 tag
```

## What Must Be True Before Every Commit
- [ ] `go test -race ./...` exits 0
- [ ] `go vet ./...` exits 0
- [ ] `go build ./...` exits 0
- [ ] No hardcoded API keys or secrets in any file
- [ ] Story acceptance criteria are all met

## What Should NEVER Be Committed
- `.env` files (only `.env.example`)
- `*.tar.gz` bundle files
- `vendor/` directory (use go modules)
- OS files: `.DS_Store`, `Thumbs.db`
- IDE files: `.idea/`
- Binary build outputs

## .gitignore (create this at S0.1)
```gitignore
# Built binary
autopsy
autopsy.exe

# Environment
.env

# Bundle files (can be large)
*.tar.gz
*.tgz

# Temp directories
tmp/

# OS
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# IDE
.idea/
*.swp
*.swo
```

## Branch Strategy
- Work directly on `main`
- No feature branches

## Final Tag (last action in S7.4)
```bash
git tag -a v1.0.0 -m "Autopsy v1.0 — AI-powered Kubernetes support bundle analyzer"
```

## What the Commit History Should Look Like
```
a1b2c3d docs(S7.4): final README polish and v1.0.0 tag
b2c3d4e feat(S7.3): docker-compose for one-command startup
c3d4e5f feat(S7.2): multi-stage Dockerfile with non-root user
d4e5f6g feat(S7.1): embed templates with go:embed and add healthz endpoint
...
x1y2z3a chore(S0.1): initialize go module and air live-reload
```

Every line is one story. No "fix stuff", no "WIP", no "update".
